TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Social Contract in Miniature: How Virtual Bargaining Supports Team Production
AU  - Zeitoun, Hossam
AU  - Melkonyan, Tigran
AU  - Chater, Nick
Y1  - 2022/01/17
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2023/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2020.0229
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2020.0229
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 432
EP  - 462
VL  - 48
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The ability of teams to self-organize and engage in spontaneous collaboration is crucial to 21st-century organizations. The large extent of nonroutine activities in such organizations hampers the effectiveness of traditional management instruments, such as monitoring effort and performance levels and exercising fiat?resulting in increasingly important self-organized collaboration. To explain how such collaboration is possible, we suggest a refinement of the psychological assumptions underpinning influential theories of the firm?specifically, concerning how people reason. We juxtapose ?Nash reasoning? (the mode of reasoning underpinning organizational economic theories of the firm) with ?virtual bargaining? (a more collaborative mode of reasoning drawing on recent research in cognitive science). Virtual bargaining enables individuals to establish, maintain, and abide by tacit ?social contracts? of their team and organization?the (often-tacit) norms, rules, roles, and responsibilities governing how employees should behave (irrespective of their personal objectives). Thus, virtual bargaining helps individuals mitigate challenges of team production, such as shirking and hold-up, in a self-organizing and self-enforcing way. We analyze the conditions under which virtual bargaining leads individuals to coordinate on enhanced effort levels in organizationally relevant settings. We outline avenues for empirically testing virtual bargaining in organizations and discuss conceptual implications.
AB  - The ability of teams to self-organize and engage in spontaneous collaboration is crucial to 21st-century organizations. The large extent of nonroutine activities in such organizations hampers the effectiveness of traditional management instruments, such as monitoring effort and performance levels and exercising fiat?resulting in increasingly important self-organized collaboration. To explain how such collaboration is possible, we suggest a refinement of the psychological assumptions underpinning influential theories of the firm?specifically, concerning how people reason. We juxtapose ?Nash reasoning? (the mode of reasoning underpinning organizational economic theories of the firm) with ?virtual bargaining? (a more collaborative mode of reasoning drawing on recent research in cognitive science). Virtual bargaining enables individuals to establish, maintain, and abide by tacit ?social contracts? of their team and organization?the (often-tacit) norms, rules, roles, and responsibilities governing how employees should behave (irrespective of their personal objectives). Thus, virtual bargaining helps individuals mitigate challenges of team production, such as shirking and hold-up, in a self-organizing and self-enforcing way. We analyze the conditions under which virtual bargaining leads individuals to coordinate on enhanced effort levels in organizationally relevant settings. We outline avenues for empirically testing virtual bargaining in organizations and discuss conceptual implications.
